    <h4>What is a typical day in your life at Bank of America?</h4>
<p><strong>9:00 – 9:30 AM:</strong> Arrive at my desk and review a dozen or so emails about
products I work on from branches that start work 2-6 hours
before London.</p>

<p><strong>9:30 – 10:00 AM:</strong> Check my calendar, so I don’t miss any meetings.
Review bugs identified by QA team.</p>

<p><strong>10:00 – 10:15 AM:</strong> Daily stand-up call on project progress.</p>

<p><strong>10:15 – 12:30 PM:</strong> Meetings with developers in other branches to
discuss any issues and concerns in more detail or continue
development efforts.</p>

<p><strong>12:30 – 1:30 PM:</strong> Lunch</p>

<p><strong>1:30 – 3:00 PM:</strong> Continue development or informal
discussions with other developers and subject matter
experts about the projects and assignments.</p>

<p><strong>3:00 – 4:00 PM:</strong> Meetings with internal business
partners to discuss requirements or changes to
the product.</p>

<p><strong>4:00 – 4:30 PM:</strong> Check in code to source control.
Check in Cruise Control that build is not broken by
my changes. Fix build if broken.</p>

<p><strong>4:30 – 5:00 PM:</strong> Send out emails identifying new
changes to QA team and other developers.</p>

<h4>What is your current assignment and primary responsibilities?</h4>
<p>I’m currently developing a reporting tool that provides statistics on straightthrough
processing of payments. This application will be used in multiple
Bank of America offices around the world to identify failed transactions. My
role also includes providing technical guidance to facilitate redevelopment
of old applications using new technologies.</p>
    
    
